First, note that the polynomial $z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1$ is equal to $\frac{z^7-1}{z-1}.$ Therefore, we can write \[z^{10}+z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1=z^{10}+z^9+\frac{z^7-1}{z-1}.\]Now, we can use the fact that $z^{10}-1=(z^5+1)(z^2+1)(z+1)(z-1)$ to see that \begin{align*}
z^{10}+z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1&=\frac{(z^{10}-1)+(z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1)}{z-1}\\
&=\frac{(z^5+1)(z^2+1)(z+1)(z-1)+(z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1)}{z-1}.
\end{align*}Thus, we want to find a value of $k$ such that $(z-1)(z^{10}+z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1)$ divides $z^k-1.$ We can see that $z=1$ is a root of $z^{10}+z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1,$ so $(z-1)$ is a factor of $z^{10}+z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1.$ Since we want the smallest value of $k,$ we can ignore this factor and focus on the quotient. Also, note that $z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1$ is symmetric, so we can write \[z^9+z^6+z^5+z^4+z+1=\frac{z^{10}-1}{z-1}-z^8=\frac{z^{10}-z^8-z+1}{z-1}.\]Thus, we want to find the smallest value of $k$ such that $\frac{z^{10}-z^8-z+1}{z-1}$ divides $z^k-1.$ We can use synthetic division to divide $z^k-1$ by $z^2+z-1:$

\[
\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{z^{k-2}} & -z^{k-3} & +z^{k-5} & -z^{k-6} & +\cdots \\
\cline{2-6}
z^2+z-1 & z^k & & & & -1 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{z^{k+2}} & +z^{k+1} & -z^{k-1} & & \\
\cline{2-4}\cline{6-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{z^{k+2}} & +z^{k+1} & -z^{k-1} & & -1 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -z^{k+2} & -z^{k+3} & +z^{k-1} & \\
\cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & z^{k+1} & -z^{k+2} & +z^{k-1} & -1 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & z^{k+1} & +z^{k} & -z^{k-2} \\
\cline{4-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & -z^{k+2} & +z^{k-1} & -z^{k-2} - 1\\
\end{array}
\]Thus, $z^k-1=(z^2+z-1)\left(z^{k-2}+z^{k-3}-z^{k-5}-z^{k-6}+\cdots\right)+(z^{k-7}-z^{k-8}-z^{k-10}+z^{k-11}).$ Since $z^{10}-z^8-z+1=(z^2+z-1)(z^8+z^7+z^6+z^5+z^4+z^3+z^2+z+1),$ we see that the remainder term on the right-hand side is equal to $z^{10}-z^8-z+1-(z^8+z^7+z^6+z^5+z^4+z^3+z^2+z+1)=z^{10}-2z^8-z^7-z^6-z^5-z^4-z^3-z+1.$ Therefore, we want to find the smallest value of $k$ such that \[\frac{z^{10}-z^8-z+1}{z-1}=\left(z^8+z^7+z^6+z^5+z^4+z^3+z^2+z+1\right)\]divides $(z^2+z-1)\left(z^{k-2}+z^{k-3}-z^{k-5}-z^{k-6}+\cdots\right)+(z^{k-7}-z^{k-8}-z^{k-10}+z^{k-11}).$ Since $z^8+z^7+z^6+z^5+z^4+z^3+z^2+z+1$ has degree $8,$ we want the degree of the quotient to be at most 8. This occurs when $k-2=10,$ so the smallest such $k$ is $k=\boxed{12}.$

